l theory, Hall examines how the nature of civility has fluctuated in the last three centuries, how it became lost, and how it was reestablished in the twentieth century following the two world wars. He also considers why civility is currently breaking down and what can be done to mitigate this threat.The Importance of Being Civil is a decisive and sophisticated addition to the discussion of civility in its modern cultural and historical contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCivil society. 0aSocial ethics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aAdam Smith.  aAdolf Hitler.  aEurope.  aEuropean Union.  aIranian communism.  aJesuit communist communities.  aKarl Marx.  aRaymond Aron.  aUnited States.  aauthenticity.  aauthoritarianism.  aautonomy.  acapitalism.  acivil behavior.  acivil nationalism.  acivil political culture.  acivil society.  acivility.  acommercial society.  acommunism.  acomparative advantage.  aconflict.  acooperative relations.  ademocracy.  adifference.  adisagreement.  adisenchantment.  adiversity.  adivision of labor.  aeconomic growth.  aeconomic success.  aeconomic theory.  aheterogeneity.  ahomogeneity.  ahuman personality.  aimmigrants.  aimperialism.  aindividuation.  aindustrial relations.  ainternational relations.  ainternational tensions.  ainternational trade rivalries.  amilitary independence.  amodern intellectuals.  amodern science.  amodern world.  amodernist ideas.  amoral development.  anationalism.  anegative resisting power.  anormal societal relations.  apersonal authenticity.  apolitical civility.  apolitical elites.  apolitical theory.  apositive sum game.  apremodern communism.  aprudence.  arealism.  areligious charisma.  